v>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/zunE7ZW</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[MartyIndependence]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Principles of topology</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/mB1gE93</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/9dRZmB9.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/mB1gE93</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[liangjianyi7]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Here's your daily reminder to drink lots of water, eat your vegetables, and punch every nazi you see.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/o3AzAc6</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/LJag0jF.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/o3AzAc6</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[ChromaticCorvid]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Trix Ant Updates!!!</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/wnRswZb</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/vf3I8Rn.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Previously on Imgur: https://imgur.com/gallery/HCXvL6H

I put the Trix down this morning at 11:00...
This was about an hour later - you can see, they're still fucking pissed...</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ZhIo1vh.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>But just now, at 1:20PM, this:</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/vD6j1mr.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>WHAT THE FUCK?</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/5UpkJho.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>WHERE'D THEY GO?!?

Did I just discover an ant repellant??</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/wnRswZb</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[ButtersTheCat]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>What happens when you try this with wild ants?</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/HCXvL6H</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ANQIDMP.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This post was in a dump recently, and it was mentioned that the reason that ants don't like Trix, is because it contains oleic acid (found in sunflower & canola oils). 

That made me wonder what would happen if you poured canola oil around an anthill...would they think there had been an ant massacre, and abandon ship? So I decided to find out.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/c6IIrE6.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Since I've never seen how ants react to Trix, myself, I got some of those, too. My subjects are Harvester Ants. They're big, and their holes are easy to find - plus, they're everywhere, here.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/mIaaIZU.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Hole #1 - it was very windy out, and we have a lot of stray and wild animals around that might eat the Trix, so I found an ant bed that was relatively safe from both, for the Trix. 

I poured a small amount near the hole, but not on it. 

The reaction was instantaneous.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/ullmEQB.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Not sure if the sound was picked up on the video, but you can literally hear them crunching it, trying to break it apart. They don't seem to know where to take it. At first, several ants tried hauling pieces off, but about an hour later, they were working together to try to get it into their hole. 

It also drew the attention of a smaller species of ant (not sure what they are), who just seemed to be checking it out.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/Qv68heG.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>(I put a stick near the hole, so I could find it quickly)</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/C0tRat5.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/SOyvS4A.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>On to the Canola oil! 

I would've preferred Sunflower oil, since it's about 80% oleic acid, versus the 60% in Canola, but Walmart didn't have any. 

I poured around half a cup near the entrance to bed #2. I misjudged the slope, and it ran right into the hole.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/hTixSGg.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>The reaction was frenzied again - some of the ants got oil on them, and we're immediately carted away by other ants, so that was interesting.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/XRczgvS.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Hole #3, I went a little further - I dug a moat, and filled it with oil. The ants seemed VERY CONFUSED by it, but nothing else 

The results on the canola oil were inconclusive, aside from them NOT FUCKING LIKING IT.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/Ac0oh1N.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/PC1ZOlo.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/vmkyV5b.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>I checked the Canola beds first, this morning.

Bed #2 appears to have resumed regular activity, mostly ignoring the oil.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/0FZcMrt.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Bed #3 still appears to be confused by the moat, but they are venturing outside of it, so the disruption to the nest seems pretty minimal.

Kind of a letdown, but it did answer my question on that.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/8ol7577.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>The Trix hole, though...is GONE.

No Trix, no harvester ants (a couple of the smaller species still walking around, but that's it).</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/5kpAgFG.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>It's like they were never even there. Where did they go? Did they take the Trix? Did an animal eat it? WTF?</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/UpT7kzj.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>It warranted further study, so I found a much larger ant hole, and poured Trix directly into it.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/w9B9gBe.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>The reaction has started out just the same, so weather and stray animals permitting, I should be able to see what happens a little closer this time.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/kfgvmDA.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>I'll post an update, when I have one available.

